Discussion. - Substitution of the  bicyclic skeleton  of the  parent  tetraene  (&)-1 with  oxy substituents is expected to induce a retarding effect on its Diels-Alder additions due to  an electronic factor (inductive effect [7]) and possibly to a steric factor (steric hindrance).  Substitution at C(4) is expected to retard the cycloadditions of the diene moiety attached  at C(2),C(3) more than that  at  C(6),C(7), in  agreement with  the  observed  decrease  of  chemoselectivity between the TCNE additions to (&)-1 and those to (+)-4  and (+)-7 [4] on  one hand  (Scheme I )  and between (&)-1 and 11-13  on the other hand (Scheme 2). The  fact  that  similar  chemoselectivities were  observed  for the  cycloadditions  of  (+)-4  and  (+)-7  can  be  explained  either  in  terms  of  an  endo-face  selectivity  for  the  dienophile  addition onto the diene moiety at C(2),C(3)’) which makes the reaction insensitive to the  change  in  bulk  between  the  4-ex0 -hydroxy  (in  (+)-4) and  4-exo -(tert-buty1)dimethyl-  silyloxy groups (in (+)-7) or in terms of a (t-Bu)Me,SiO group that can turn away from  the path of the dienophile attack onto the exo-face of the diene moiety attached at C(2),  C(3)’). The latter hypothesis cannot be ruled out by Dreiding models. The removal of the  1-methoxy group in (+)-4  and (+)-7 and introduction of  a hydroxy,  alkoxy, or silyloxy  groups at the syn-position  of C(8) (see 11-15)  should  not affect  differentially  the elec-  tronic properties of the two diene moieties, to a first approximation.
